22
0:01:44,720 --> 0:01:48,160
In the preparation for and the writing of this course, I have encountered a strange tendency,

23
0:01:48,160 --> 0:01:51,520
wherein the claim that people ought not violate the rights of others is apparently a controversial

24
0:01:51,520 --> 0:01:55,360
one, even among Austrians. This is indicative of a severe problem in Austro-libertarian

25
0:01:55,360 --> 0:01:58,400
circles that deserves a dedicated section of this course to properly address.

26
0:01:58,400 --> 0:02:02,240
The root for this problem is that many reject the core definition of law as a subset of ethics,

27
0:02:02,240 --> 0:02:05,920
claiming instead that there is such a thing as a virtuous crime. The paragon example would be a

28
0:02:05,920 --> 0:02:09,680
man who is about to commit suicide by jumping off of a cliff. And the only way to save this man

29
0:02:09,680 --> 0:02:12,880
is to violate his rights by grabbing him and dragging him away from the cliff's edge.

30
0:02:12,880 --> 0:02:16,880
These contextualist-libertarians would have it that whether a crime is moral or not depends on

31
0:02:16,880 --> 0:02:21,120
extra-legal context. I believe much of the confusion on this topic stems from the fact that many

32
0:02:21,120 --> 0:02:25,120
libertarians at least appear to be somewhat inconsistent. At some points indicating that law

33
0:02:25,120 --> 0:02:29,120
is indeed a subset of ethics and at other points rejecting this position. Rothbard explicitly

34
0:02:29,120 --> 0:02:33,280
states his work on pollution, that law is a subset of ethics and a set of ought or normative

35
0:02:33,280 --> 0:02:37,120
propositions. But his discussion of lifeboat scenarios in The Ethics of Liberty, is commonly

36
0:02:37,120 --> 0:02:41,200
cited to negate this point. Rothbard presents the conundrum as follows:

37
0:02:41,200 --> 0:02:45,680
QUOTE that the existence of extreme or lifeboat situations disproves any theory of absolute property rights,

38
0:02:45,680 --> 0:02:49,760
or indeed of any absolute rights of self-ownership whatsoever. It is claimed that since any theory

39
0:02:49,760 --> 0:02:53,680
of individual rights seems to break down or works unsatisfactorily in such fortunately rare

40
0:02:53,680 --> 0:02:58,000
situations, therefore there can be no concept of inviolable rights at all. In a typical lifeboat

41
0:02:58,000 --> 0:03:01,920
situation there are, let us say, eight places in a lifeboat putting out from a sinking ship,

42
0:03:01,920 --> 0:03:05,360
END QUOTE and there are more than eight people wishing to be saved. Who then is to decide who should

43
0:03:05,360 --> 0:03:09,120
On its face, this appears to not present any serious problem to

44
0:03:09,120 --> 0:03:12,640
the theory presented in this course. The fact that the truth of the matter is unsatisfactory

45
0:03:12,640 --> 0:03:16,720
or makes someone upset or look like a bad guy for presenting it does not constitute a refutation

46
0:03:16,720 --> 0:03:21,440
of said truth. Indeed, to warp one's ethics to suit one's intuition such that any "unsatisfactory"

47
0:03:21,440 --> 0:03:25,200
results are purged would be to surrender oneself to accepting the mystic power of whim to grant

48
0:03:25,200 --> 0:03:29,520
truth, thus tainting an otherwise sound epistemology, thus I shall proceed with the analysis without

49
0:03:29,520 --> 0:03:33,600
caring about how nasty-sounding the conclusion reached may be. In the first place we have a scarcity,

50
0:03:33,600 --> 0:03:37,600
only eight spots in a lifeboat and more than eight people, thus property rights must be assigned.

51
0:03:37,600 --> 0:03:41,520
Presumably this lifeboat did not materialise in nature and was instead built by or purchased

52
0:03:41,520 --> 0:03:45,680
by whomever owns the boat, thus it is he who gets the right to say who gets a spot, perhaps he makes

53
0:03:45,680 --> 0:03:49,840
a rule that women and children go first, perhaps he decides that crewmates get priority over customers

54
0:03:49,840 --> 0:03:54,400
and so on. Whatever arbitrary rules he sets ought be abided. Now what of the situation where the

55
0:03:54,400 --> 0:03:58,320
owner set no rules forth and has died abandoning lifeboat to the domain of nature? We surely

56
0:03:58,320 --> 0:04:02,720
have our solution in the homesteading principle. First come, first served. If you get to a spot in the

57
0:04:02,720 --> 0:04:07,040
lifeboat you're thus using said spot and thus get to dictate how it is to be used. Presumably

58
0:04:07,040 --> 0:04:10,800
you want it to be used to save yourself. This might be horribly unfair to those who are slower or

59
0:04:10,800 --> 0:04:14,800
started further away from the lifeboat, but tough luck! Life isn't fair and neither is law.

60
0:04:14,800 --> 0:04:19,360
The prime goal of law is justice, not fairness. What, after all, would be the alternative? That

61
0:04:19,360 --> 0:04:22,960
people who are slower to get to the boat, i.e. late comers are the ones who should get a spot?

62
0:04:22,960 --> 0:04:26,160
Well, then the people they kick out could just immediately return to the boat as an even later

63
0:04:26,160 --> 0:04:29,920
comer, thus entering us into an endless dance of groups getting in and out of the boat.

64
0:04:29,920 --> 0:04:33,680
Everyone would be equal, but everyone would be dead. It seems that Rothbard came to the same conclusion:

65
0:04:33,680 --> 0:04:37,520
QUOTE If the owner of the boat, or his representative, e.g. the captain of the ship,

66
0:04:37,520 --> 0:04:41,600
has died in the wreck, and if he has not laid down no rules in advance of the wreck for allocation

67
0:04:41,600 --> 0:04:45,280
of seats in such a crisis, then the lifeboat may be considered at least temporarily for the

68
0:04:45,280 --> 0:04:49,360
emergency, abandoned, and therefore unowned. At this point, our rules for unowned property

69
0:04:49,360 --> 0:04:53,360
come into play, namely that unowned resources become the property of the first people possessing

70
0:04:53,360 --> 0:04:57,280
them. In short, the first eight people to reach the boat are, in our theory, the proper owners

71
0:04:57,280 --> 0:05:00,960
and users of the boat. Anyone who throws them out of the boat then commits an act of aggression

72
0:05:00,960 --> 0:05:04,720
in violating the property right of the homesteader he throws out of the boat. After he returns to

73
0:05:04,720 --> 0:05:08,640
shore, then the aggressive becomes liable for prosecution for his act of violation of property

74
0:05:08,640 --> 0:05:11,920
right, as well, perhaps for the murder of the person he rejected out of the boat.

75
0:05:11,920 --> 0:05:15,440
Rothbard continues with the following. In the first place, a lifeboat situation is hardly a

76
0:05:15,440 --> 0:05:19,040
valid test of a theory of rights, or any moral theory whatsoever. Problems of moral theory

77
0:05:19,040 --> 0:05:23,040
in such an extreme situation do not invalidate a theory in normal situations. In any sphere of

78
0:05:23,040 --> 0:05:26,960
moral theory, we are trying to affirm an ethic for man, based on his nature and the nature of the

79
0:05:26,960 --> 0:05:31,760
world, and this precisely means for normal nature, for the way life usually is, and not for rare or

80
0:05:31,760 --> 0:05:36,560
abnormal situations, is a wise maxim of law for precisely this reason that hard cases make bad

81
0:05:36,560 --> 0:05:40,320
law. We are trying to frame an ethic for the way men generally live in the world. We are not,

82
0:05:40,320 --> 0:05:43,920
after all, interested in framing an ethic that focuses on situations that are rare, extreme,

83
0:05:43,920 --> 0:05:47,360
and not generally encountered. Let's take an example to illustrate their point.

84
0:05:47,360 --> 0:05:50,800
Outside the sphere of property rights, or rights in general, and within the sphere of ordinary

85
0:05:50,800 --> 0:05:54,560
ethical values. Most people would concede the principle that it is ethical for a parent to save

86
0:05:54,560 --> 0:05:59,040
his child from drowning, but then our lifeboat skeptic could arise, and our all is challenged.

87
0:05:59,040 --> 0:06:02,320
Aha, but suppose that two of your children are drowning, and you can only save one. Which

88
0:06:02,320 --> 0:06:05,600
child would you choose? And doesn't the fact that you'd have to let one child die and they get the

89
0:06:05,600 --> 0:06:08,960
very moral principle that you should save your drowning child? I doubt whether many ethicists

90
0:06:08,960 --> 0:06:12,560
would throw over the moral desirability or principle of saving one's child because it

91
0:06:12,560 --> 0:06:16,480
END QUOTEcould not be fully applied in such a lifeboat situation. Yet why should the lifeboat case be

92
0:06:16,480 --> 0:06:20,160
The response here indicates that there are at least two different spheres of ethics.

93
0:06:20,160 --> 0:06:25,120
One for normal situations, and one for abnormal ones. It is not clear, however,

94
0:06:25,120 --> 0:06:28,480
how on earth it could be possible to make a non-arbitrary distinction between normal and

95
0:06:28,480 --> 0:06:32,320
abnormal ethical conundrums. Moreover, as such a principled distinction cannot be made between

96
0:06:32,320 --> 0:06:36,240
normal and abnormal such a theory be particularistic and thus irrational. That is to say, there are

97
0:06:36,240 --> 0:06:40,160
certainly many differences that one could use to define normal as opposed to abnormal. Say that

98
0:06:40,160 --> 0:06:44,000
situations where red shirts are worn are abnormal, and the ones where red shirts are not worn,

99
0:06:44,000 --> 0:06:47,840
the situation is normal. That would be a difference, but the difference is not relevant to ethical

100
0:06:47,840 --> 0:06:52,480
theory. Thus a rational norm must apply to both classes of situations in order to be universal,

101
0:06:52,480 --> 0:06:56,080
as opposed to particular. Until such a principled difference can be found to define normal as

102
0:06:56,080 --> 0:07:00,240
opposed to abnormal, we are stuck with universal norms having to apply to both classes, and thus

103
0:07:00,240 --> 0:07:03,840
there are not two "spheres" of moral theory. That is to say, it couldn't be the case that

104
0:07:03,840 --> 0:07:08,400
property rights hold normally, but not abnormally. Such would be a particularistic property norm,

105
0:07:08,400 --> 0:07:12,240
and thus an irrational one. I must now consider Rothbard's drowning children hypothetical.

106
0:07:12,240 --> 0:07:15,440
In the case of a single child, it is assumed that parent can save them, and in the case of

107
0:07:15,440 --> 0:07:19,040
two children it is assumed that only one can be saved. There are indeed certain similarities

108
0:07:19,040 --> 0:07:22,560
between the drowning children and Lifeboat, so the case of two children, one will die, and one will

109
0:07:22,560 --> 0:07:26,160
live. For the Lifeboat, eight will live, and others will die. The question is how to determine

110
0:07:26,160 --> 0:07:29,120
who should live and who should die. We have our solution in the case of the Lifeboat,

111
0:07:29,120 --> 0:07:32,080
and it strikes me that this course provides a similar ability to answer the drowning children

112
0:07:32,080 --> 0:07:35,840
hypothetical. The mother cannot physically save both, and thus it is surely a matter of personal

113
0:07:35,840 --> 0:07:39,440
preference which one she saves. And why should she be expected to act any differently? It would

114
0:07:39,440 --> 0:07:43,200
be logically impossible for her to pick the one that she would prefer not to save, and thus the

115
0:07:43,200 --> 0:07:46,880
only alternative would be to let both drown. Surely we can easily sum this up in a universal

116
0:07:46,880 --> 0:07:50,480
principle. Guardians ought save their children from drowning insofar as they have the ability

117
0:07:50,480 --> 0:07:53,840
to. It is not my claim that this principle has been proven, after all this is a law course,

118
0:07:53,840 --> 0:07:57,200
not a course on ethics in general, but I can't see how this would not be universal,

119
0:07:57,200 --> 0:08:01,120
and it certainly seems that it easily deals with Rothbard's hypothetical opponent.

120
0:08:01,120 --> 0:08:05,760
Rothbard seemingly goes forth with his multi-sphere model:

121
0:08:05,760 --> 0:08:09,120
to our theory as follows. That theory of property rights, or even of self-ownership,

122
0:08:09,120 --> 0:08:12,640
is driveable from the conditions by which man survives and flourishes in this world,

123
0:08:12,640 --> 0:08:16,400
and that therefore, in this kind of extreme situation, or mass faced with the choice of either

124
0:08:16,400 --> 0:08:20,240
saving himself or violating the property rights of the Lifeboat owner, or in the above example of

125
0:08:20,240 --> 0:08:23,920
the homesteader of the boat, and it is ridiculous to expect him to surrender his life on behalf

126
0:08:23,920 --> 0:08:27,280
of the abstract principle of property rights. Because of this kind of consideration, many

127
0:08:27,280 --> 0:08:30,720
libertarians who otherwise believe in property rights gravely weaken them on behalf of the

128
0:08:30,720 --> 0:08:34,560
contextualist contention that, given a choice between his life and a grazing against someone

129
0:08:34,560 --> 0:08:38,000
else's property or even life, it is moral for him to commit the aggression, and that therefore,

130
0:08:38,000 --> 0:08:41,440
in such a situation, these property rights cease to exist. The error here on the part of

131
0:08:41,440 --> 0:08:44,800
the contentious libertarian is to confuse the question of the moral course of action for the

132
0:08:44,800 --> 0:08:48,560
person in such a tragic situation, with a totally separate question of whether or not his seizing

133
0:08:48,560 --> 0:08:52,320
of Lifeboat or Planck Space by force constitutes an invasion of someone else's property right,

134
0:08:52,320 --> 0:08:56,240
for we are not in constructing a theory of liberty and property, i.e. a political ethic,

135
0:08:56,240 --> 0:09:00,240
concerned with all personal moral principles. We are not here with concern whether it is moral

136
0:09:00,240 --> 0:09:04,640
or immoral for someone to lie, to be a good person, to develop his faculties, or be kind or mean to

137
0:09:04,640 --> 0:09:08,560
his neighbours. We are concerned in this sort of discussion solely with such political ethical

138
0:09:08,560 --> 0:09:12,640
questions as the proper rule of violence, the sphere of rights, or the definitions of criminality

139
0:09:12,640 --> 0:09:16,160
and aggression. Whether or not it is moral or immoral for Smith, the fellow excluded by the

140
0:09:16,160 --> 0:09:19,440
owner from the Planck or the Lifeboat, to force someone else out of the Lifeboat or whether he

141
0:09:19,440 --> 0:09:23,520
END QUOTE should die heroically instead, is not our concern and not the proper concern of a theory of political

142
0:09:23,520 --> 0:09:27,520
On a first glance, it would seem that Rothbard is adopting a dichotomy between law and ethics,

143
0:09:27,520 --> 0:09:31,520
and this passage would mean sighted to me numerous times to that effect. But to my eye, this is only

144
0:09:31,520 --> 0:09:35,040
one of multiple valid interpretations of Rothbard's writing here. It appears to me that he is merely

145
0:09:35,040 --> 0:09:38,800
hedging his bets and ignoring the questions of ethics as a whole and focusing in on the area

146
0:09:38,800 --> 0:09:42,800
that he has expertise in. This highlights why Rothbard saw fit to analyse the Lifeboat scenario

147
0:09:42,800 --> 0:09:47,440
to "ordinary ethical values;" if law was not a subset of ethics, i.e. if it did not deal with

148
0:09:47,440 --> 0:09:51,840
ought statements, such an analogy would be incoherent. Furthermore, Rothbard is correct here that we

149
0:09:51,840 --> 0:09:56,000
are not, in constructing a theory of liberty and property, concerned with all personal moral

150
0:09:56,000 --> 0:09:59,840
principles. We are rather only concerned with those moral principles that pertain to conflicts

151
0:09:59,840 --> 0:10:04,560
over scarce means. This does not, as the critics claim, demonstrate that law and ethics are disconnected

152
0:10:04,560 --> 0:10:08,320
fields. Clearly, if we are concerned with a subset of all moral principles which deals specifically

153
0:10:08,320 --> 0:10:13,120
with conflicts in doing law, then law itself is a subset of morality in general. This analysis is

154
0:10:13,120 --> 0:10:16,480
also consistent with Rothbard's claim that whether or not it is moral or immoral for Smith,

155
0:10:16,480 --> 0:10:19,840
the fellow excluded by the owner from the plank or the Lifeboat, to force someone else out of the

156
0:10:19,840 --> 0:10:23,840
Lifeboat, or whether he should die heroically instead, is not our concern and not the proper

157
0:10:23,840 --> 0:10:27,520
concern of a theory of political ethics. It very much appears to me that Rothbard is merely leaving

158
0:10:27,520 --> 0:10:31,360
the floor open for his legal theory to be compatible with any outside ethical theory that one may come

159
0:10:31,360 --> 0:10:35,840
up with, even one which would allow for contradictions between "personal" and "political" ethics. Of course,

160
0:10:35,840 --> 0:10:39,840
such a theory would be false, but that is not the concern of Rothbard qua legal theorist.

161
0:10:39,840 --> 0:10:43,760
This becomes clear in a footnote attached to the end of the above paragraph, commenting on an example

162
0:10:43,760 --> 0:10:47,120
where two men are floating in the water and there's a plank that can save only one of them:

163
0:10:47,120 --> 0:10:50,480
QUOTE Eric Mack's example fails to show a necessary conflict between property rights and moral

164
0:10:50,480 --> 0:10:54,080
principles. The conflict in his example is between property rights and the dictates of prudence

165
0:10:54,080 --> 0:10:58,000
or self-interest, but the latter is only dominated morality if one adopts moral equalism,

166
0:10:58,000 --> 0:11:01,760
END QUOTE which indeed Professor Mack does, but which is only one possible moral theory.

167
0:11:01,760 --> 0:11:05,920
This makes it abundantly clear to me that Rothbard is, as I claim, simply trying to make his ethic as narrow

168
0:11:05,920 --> 0:11:10,400
as possible such that it may be slotted into any general ethical theory.

169
0:11:10,400 --> 0:11:14,000
QUOTE The crucial point is that even if the contextualist libertarians may say that,

170
0:11:14,000 --> 0:11:18,480
given the tragic context, Smith should throw someone else out of the lifeboat to save his own life,

171
0:11:18,480 --> 0:11:22,880
he is still committing, at the very least, invasion of property rights, and probably also

172
0:11:22,880 --> 0:11:26,640
murder of the person thrown out, so that even if one says that he should try and save his life

173
0:11:26,640 --> 0:11:31,120
by forcibly grabbing a seat in the lifeboat, he is still, in our view, liable to prosecution as

174
0:11:31,120 --> 0:11:35,360
a criminal invader of property right, and perhaps as a murderer as well. After he's convicted,

175
0:11:35,360 --> 0:11:39,440
it would be the right of the lifeboat owner or the heir of the person tossed out to forgive Smith,

176
0:11:39,440 --> 0:11:43,520
to pardon him because of the unusual circumstances, but it would also be the right not to pardon

177
0:11:43,520 --> 0:11:47,200
and to proceed with the full force of their legal right to punish. Once again, we are concerned in

178
0:11:47,200 --> 0:11:51,120
this theory with the rights of the case, not, with whether or not a person chooses to voluntarily

179
0:11:51,120 --> 0:11:54,720
exercise his rights. In our view, the property owner or the heir of the killed would have the

180
0:11:54,720 --> 0:11:59,200
right to prosecute and to exact proper punishment upon the aggressor. The fallacy of the contextualists

181
0:11:59,200 --> 0:12:02,880
is to confuse considerations of individual personal morality, what should Smith do,

182
0:12:02,880 --> 0:12:06,800
END QUOTE with the question of the rights of the case. The right to property continues, then, to be absolute,

183
0:12:06,800 --> 0:12:10,880
Again, Rothbard's use of the even if disclaimer prior to the hypothetical proof

184
0:12:10,880 --> 0:12:14,640
that Smith should throw someone out of the lifeboat is a crystal-clear

185
0:12:14,640 --> 0:12:18,720
signal that Rothbard is merely entertaining this as a hypothetical counter to his thesis.

186
0:12:18,720 --> 0:12:22,320
What Rothbard has done is that he is shown his theory of property rights to hold, even if

187
0:12:22,320 --> 0:12:25,600
someone were to prove that there are separate personal and political spheres of ethics.

188
0:12:25,600 --> 0:12:29,840
To reiterate, Rothbard has not here accepted that there is indeed such a proof, all he has done

189
0:12:29,840 --> 0:12:33,440
is shown that the existence of such a proof is irrelevant to his legal theory. Of course,

190
0:12:33,440 --> 0:12:37,280
such a proof does not exist, as said multi-sphere ethics would be a polylogism.

191
0:12:37,280 --> 0:12:41,680
Ought is ought, there is not ought-but-personal, and a separate ought-but-political, there is only ought.

192
0:12:41,680 --> 0:12:45,520
Confusion on this matter comes down to colloquial usage of the word ought. In sentences like,

193
0:12:45,520 --> 0:12:48,560
you ought wear a coat because you don't want to get wet. There are two ways we can interpret

194
0:12:48,560 --> 0:12:51,760
this statement. Either we assume that ought is being used in its precise logical meaning,

195
0:12:51,760 --> 0:12:55,120
or we assume it is being used as prudential advice. In the former case, the statement is

196
0:12:55,120 --> 0:12:58,160
simply invalid. It does not follow from the fact that a person doesn't want to get wet,

